Although divorce results in substantial costs for the individuals involved and sometimes for their children, women interviewed in the study viewed separation from an abusive spouse as a positive solution. However, when a woman is not financially dependent on her husband, separating from him has limited impacts. On the other hand, if the woman is more physically dependent on her spouse, a divorce has more severe consequences.

For example, women who are employed often have different conditions for their divorce than their counterparts who are unemployed. In a divorce, uninsured women are often unable to relocate to their home country. These factors make divorce a very complex decision.

The researchers studied a total of 224 Pakistani women in Dubai who were undergoing divorce. They measured attitudes towards divorce by utilizing a five-point scale. In reference to attitudes toward divorce, the authors wrote, "Participants were moderately supportive (3.00 ± 0.96 scores)." A total of 65.7 percent felt their divorce was a positive event.

Those women without insurance were by far the most likely to be negatively affected by divorce. A total of 73.3 percent of the women who were uninsured stated they had negative feelings towards divorce, while only 51.6 percent of the insurance group showed negative attitudes.
